summary:
In this research we discuss the problems of extraterritorial application of human rights treaties having in mind one real case of a distressed vessel at high seas. The controversial issue is the definition of what “effective control” means for the ECHR and the ICPPR and if the states have positive obligations to prevent threats to the human right to life according to these conventions.

Our findings can be summarized as follows:
•	The European Court of Human Rights’s case law is changing and there is an enlargement of the functional approach to jurisdiction regarding human rights law;
•	There are new theoretical efforts to explain that the concept of jurisdiction is different in international human rights law and is not limited to a territorial approach;
•	The concept of “jurisdiction” within the meaning of Article 1 of the ECHR is not necessarily restricted to the national territory of the contracting parties and exceptional circumstances the acts of States performed outside their territory or which produce effects there (“extra-territorial act”) may amount to exercise by them of their jurisdiction;
•	According to ECHR case law, a State can exercise jurisdiction extra-territorially through the assertion of authority and control by its agents over an individual or individuals;
•	Jurisdiction should extend to the situations effectively under the control of a state and in which the State may ensure the protection of the full range of the rights protected under human rights conventions;
•	It is possible to argue that the correct approach under the ICCPR is based on the universal nature of human rights, irrespective of whether the country where the alleged extraterritorial violations occur is a party to the ICCPR.

